After 1 month in Sri Lanka, not including flights, this is what we’ve spent per person… 🏠 £143 on accommodation - less than £5 per night on average! 🛺 £64 on transport which includes buses, trains and tuk tuks 🍜 £437 on food - £14.50 per day on average! 🐘 £82 on activities which includes our safari and other small admission fees 💊 £32 on miscellaneous, which covers Kitt’s tattoo and random bits from the pharmacy 📞 £19.30 each on phone data for the month So, the grand total spend for Sri Lanka was £777 per person, which takes us to a fraction over £25 per person per day over 30 days! TIPS: ✨A room based on 2 people sharing was nearly always cheaper than a hostel (if you can go without aircon, this saves $$ too!) ✨ Buying train tickets are cheaper at the station than online platforms such as 12Go - buy ahead of time to avoid them selling out! ✨ This one’s a given, but opt for local and street food to save pennies ✨ ‘Pickme’ is a very cheap way of getting taxis in Sri Lanka, and any public transport is extremely low cost! ✨ We use ‘Get Nomad’ for our phone data on an eSim - this saves time and effort (compared with local sim) and easy to top up ✨ Lots of places in Sri Lanka charge for foreigners to enter such as parks. Even some temples would charge 15x the price of locals. Often we would find other things to do that weren’t necessarily on ‘top 10’ lists How did we do?! Ja die Zeit auf Sri Lanka war schön, aber auch intensiv. Und vieles hier ist anders, als zuhause in Deutschland, weshalb manches ungewohnt für uns war und wir uns auch in dieser kurzen Zeit nicht dran gewöhnen konnten oder wollten. Hier unsere 3 Dinge, die wir nicht vermissen werden. Nr.1 das Plastik am Strand, auch Sri Lanka ist hiervon nicht verschont geblieben und an vielen Ecken wird Plastikmüll angespült. Leider wird auch beim Einkaufen bzw Alltag noch sehr viel Plastik verbraucht. Nr.2 häufig hatten wir beim Essen Sandkörner zwischen den Zähnen. Wir vermuten, dass es oft von den Frühlingszwiebeln bzw. dem Lauch kam. Das tat schon manchmal beim plötzlichen aufbeißen sehr weh. Nr. 3 die Busse dort waren wirklich verrückt und wir hatten teilweise echt Angst vor ihnen. Sie hupen direkt neben dir als Fußgänger mit völlig übertönten Hupen, das sorgt richtig für Adrenalinausschüttung. Ja so ein Urlaub in einem fremden Land bringt auch neue Erfahrungen und dafür sind wir trotzdem dankbar, auch wenn wir sie definitiv nicht vermissen werden.

Kennst du diesen Ort? Ta Prohm, auch bekannt als der Tomb-Raider-Tempel ist eine verlassene Tempelanlage aus dem 12. Jhdt im Westen Kambodschas nahe der Stadt Siem Reap. Der Tempel, welcher ursprünglich als Kloster und Universität diente, ist bekannt für seine einzigartige Atmosphäre. In dieser Anlage verbindet sich die alte Stätte mit der Natur auf spektakuläre Weise. Gigantische Bäume, unter anderem Würgefeigen wachsen mittlerweile auf den Mauern und haben große Teile des Bauwerkes mit Ihren kräftigen Wurzeln umschlungen. Ta Prohm wurde im Vergleich zu anderen Tempeln nicht restauriert, um die Ursprünglichkeit beizubehalten. Dank dieser Verschmelzung mit der Natur, diente er 2001 als Kulisse für das Videospiel Tomb Raider und die Abenteuer von Lara Croft. Ta Prohm gehört mit vielen anderen Tempeln zusammen die größte Religiöse Stätte rund um Angkor Wat in Kambodscha, die auf jeden Fall einen Besuch wert ist. Warst du schon dort oder steht dieses Ziel auf deiner Bucketlist?

I'll be reviewing running routes from all over the world. Running has been my daily ritual for the past ten years, helping me through some tough times. For the last fourteen months, I've been on an incredible journey across sixteen countries, and no matter where I am, running is a must for me. However, I've noticed a lack of detailed information about running routes, especially in less-traveled locations. That's why I'm creating a series of videos reviewing hundreds of different runs from various places around the globe. In each video, I'll share insights about the location and the route itself. I'll only feature routes I'd personally recommend—whether they're fast, flat, and long, or a challenging uphill with breathtaking views. These routes aren't just great runs; they're also fantastic ways to explore new places. If any of the routes catch your eye, just comment "run" on the video, and I'll share the Strava route with you. You don't need to be super fit or fast to try these routes—I'm not! I do enjoy long distances, so you'll find everything from 5Ks to marathons in my reviews. Join me as we discover amazing running routes and explore the world together!

This Some kind of tourists in our existence The Black Desert is an area of volcano-shaped and widely separated mounds in western Egypt, stretching for around 30 kilometres (19 miles) between the White Desert in the south and the Bahariya Oasis in the north. Basalt sills cover the majority of its mounds, giving them their distinctive black appearance. The Black Desert's mounds, which may reach heights of 100 metres (328 feet), vary in size, composition, height, and shape, with some being black due to iron quartzite and others being more reddish due to iron sandstone. Volcanic hills on the fringes of the Black Desert show that black volcanic dolerite erupted 180 million years ago, indicating the Jurassic era. 1 Its soooo beautiful. It is volcano's lava. When you approach the mountain the lava are balck rocks. When you start walking up the mountain and you approach the summit, you realize that the volcano's lava made the rocks all pressed one against each other. Something phenominal. You just have to wear good climing boots or shoes. Some rocks are slippery. Must be careful. It is the highest summit in the black desert. I have never immagined that a desert can be or have a magical view 2 The Black Desert is located North from the White Desert, closer to Bahariya than Farafra. The name comes from the black volcanic hills and eroded material covering the sand with black stones and powder. The darkness contrasts with what you will experience few dozens of kilometers later, the White Desert, adding to the variety of Egyptian deserts. Winter and early spring nights are pretty chilly, so remember to take a good sleeping bag if you plan camping. I do recommend some camping, if for nothing else but the unique experience of sunrise and sunset among the black hills.

This is Laos, Part 1. Unbelievable country, probably the most authentic place we've been to so far in SE Asia and yet to be fully taken over by tourists. So many memories here, and we almost decided to skip it! 🤯 Some of the main highlights of our time here include jungle trekking followed by a night in a village homestay, swimming in lagoons and waterfalls, and of course the perfect sunsets 🙌 Really glad we came here, hopefully this inspires you to visit too!
